.TH "URLPATTERN.TEST" "3JS" "August 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
URLPattern.test \- URLPattern: test() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]test()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]URLPattern\f[R]
interface takes a URL string or object of URL parts, and returns a
boolean indicating if the given input matches the current pattern.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
test(input)
test(url)
test(url, baseURL)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]input\f[R]
An object providing the individual URL parts.
The object members can be any of \f[CR]protocol\f[R],
\f[CR]username\f[R], \f[CR]password\f[R], \f[CR]hostname\f[R],
\f[CR]port\f[R], \f[CR]pathname\f[R], \f[CR]search\f[R],
\f[CR]hash\f[R], or \f[CR]baseURL\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]url\f[R]
A string defining an absolute or relative URL.
If a relative URL, then \f[CR]baseURL\f[R] must also be provided and
together they must resolve to an absolute URL.
If the input cannot be parsed, or a relative URL without a base URL is
provided, the method will return \f[CR]false\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]baseURL\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string representing the base URL to use in cases where \f[CR]url\f[R]
is a relative URL.
If not specified, it defaults to \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
If provided but the base URL cannot be parsed, the method will return
\f[CR]false\f[R].
.PP
URL parts that are not specified in the \f[CR]url\f[R]/\f[CR]input\f[R]
may be inherited from a base URL in some circumstances.
Omitted parts are treated as empty strings.
.SS Return value
A \f[CR]boolean\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Indicates that a \f[CR]baseURL\f[R] is provided when an \f[CR]input\f[R]
object is passed (it should only be passed with the \f[CR]url\f[R]
string).
.SH DESCRIPTION
The method is called on a \f[CR]URLPattern\f[R], specifying an input url
as a string with an optional base URL, or as object with properties for
each URL\-part.
.PP
The method returns \f[CR]true\f[R] if all components of the test
URL/input match all components of the pattern, and \f[CR]false\f[R] if
any component don\(cqt match.
The method also returns \f[CR]false\f[R] if a relative \f[CR]url\f[R] is
passed but \f[CR]baseURL\f[R] is not specified (an absolute test URL
cannot be resolved).
Note that when passing an \f[CR]input\f[R] object,
\f[CR]input.baseURL\f[R] is always optional.
.SS Inheritance from a BaseURL
URL\-parts that are more specific than the least\-specific part defined
in the \f[CR]url\f[R] can be inherited from \f[CR]baseURL\f[R] (or from
\f[CR]input.baseURL\f[R] for \f[CR]input\f[R]).
Intuitively this means that if the \f[CR]pathname\f[R] part is specified
in the input, the parts to its left in a URL may be inherited from the
base URL (\f[CR]protocol\f[R], \f[CR]hostname\f[R] and \f[CR]port\f[R]),
while the parts to its right may not (\f[CR]search\f[R] and
\f[CR]hash\f[R]).
The \f[CR]username\f[R] and \f[CR]password\f[R] are never inherited from
a base URL.
.PP
For more information see Inheritance from a BaseURL in the API overview.
.SH EXAMPLES
The examples shows how to use the \f[CR]test()\f[R] method to match a
URL against a pattern.
In each case the result of the \f[CR]test()\f[R] is printed to the
console.
.SS Testing an absolute URL
First we define the pattern to use for matching URLs.
This pattern matches against URLs that have either \f[CR]http\f[R] or
\f[CR]https\f[R] protocol, are subdomains of \f[CR].example.com\f[R] and
have a path that is \f[CR]/books/\f[R] followed by any value.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] pattern = \f[B]new\f[R] URLPattern(\(dqhttp{s}?://*.example.com/books/:id\(dq);
.EE
.PP
Next we match against two absolute URL strings.
The first matches but the second doesn\(cqt, because the test URL is not
a subdomain of \f[CR]example.com\f[R].
.IP
.EX
console.log(pattern.test(\(dqhttps://store.example.com/books/123\(dq)); \f[I]// true\f[R]
console.log(pattern.test(\(dqhttps://example.com/books/123\(dq)); \f[I]// false\f[R]
.EE
.SS Testing a relative URL
This example uses the same pattern as before to test against a number of
relative URLs.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] pattern = \f[B]new\f[R] URLPattern(\(dqhttp{s}?://*.example.com/books/:id\(dq);
.EE
.PP
Next we match against some relative URLs.
The case matches as the resolved URL is
\f[CR]https://store.example.com/books/123\f[R], while the second does
note because the resolved URL is not a subdomain of
\f[CR]example.com\f[R].
.IP
.EX
console.log(pattern.test(\(dq/books/123\(dq, \(dqhttp://store.example.com\(dq)); \f[I]// true\f[R]
console.log(pattern.test(\(dq/books/123\(dq, \(dqhttp://example.com\(dq)); \f[I]// false\f[R]
.EE
.PP
This test does not match because the provided URL is relative and no
baseURL is provided.
Note that you can define a test that matches against just a pathname,
but you need to use the object input.
.IP
.EX
console.log(pattern.test(\(dq/books/123\(dq)); \f[I]// false\f[R]
.EE
.PP
This test does not match because the base URL is not a valid URL, and
together with the \f[CR]/books/123\f[R] does not resolve to an absolute
URL.
.IP
.EX
console.log(pattern.test(\(dq/books/123\(dq, \(dqdata:text/plain,hello world!\(dq)); \f[I]// false\f[R]
.EE
.SS Testing an URL object
This example uses the same pattern as before to test against a number of
URLs defined as structured objects.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] pattern = \f[B]new\f[R] URLPattern(\(dqhttp{s}?://*.example.com/books/:id\(dq);
.EE
.PP
The first case matches because it defines a match exactly against each
part of the pattern:
.IP
.EX
console.log(
  pattern.test({
    protocol: \(dqhttps\(dq,
    hostname: \(dqstore.example.com\(dq,
    pathname: \(dq/books/123\(dq,
  }),
); \f[I]// true\f[R]
.EE
.PP
In this code the pathname is present and the missing parts are supplied
in the \f[CR]baseURL\f[R].
The result is the same as the previous code.
.IP
.EX
console.log(
  pattern.test({
    pathname: \(dq/books/123\(dq,
    baseURL: \(dqhttp://store.example.com\(dq,
  }),
); \f[I]// true\f[R]
.EE
.PP
This structured URL does not match the pattern, because the protocol is
\f[CR]file\f[R] (not \f[CR]https\f[R] or \f[CR]http\f[R]).
.IP
.EX
console.log(
  pattern.test({
    protocol: \(dqfile\(dq,
    hostname: \(dqstore.example.com\(dq,
    pathname: \(dq/books/123\(dq,
  }),
); \f[I]// false\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
A polyfill of \f[CR]URLPattern\f[R] is available \c
.UR https://github.com/kenchris/urlpattern-polyfill
on GitHub
.UE \c
